07247nam a22009375i 9780812208184DE-B159720220424125308.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220424t20132013pau    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)979684965  a97808122081847 a10.9783/97808122081842doi  a(DE-B1597)449704  a(OCoLC)859160945  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 7aPOL0070002bisacsh04a323.6223  aMD 4600qSEPA2rvk0(DE-625)rvk/122514:00aMultilevel Citizenship /ced. by Willem Maas. 1aPhiladelphia : bUniversity of Pennsylvania Press, c[2013] 4c©2013  a1 online resource (288 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aDemocracy, Citizenship, and Constitutionalism00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tChapter 1. Varieties of Multilevel Citizenship -- tPART I. Migrants and Migrations -- tChapter 2. Denizen Enfranchisement and Flexible Citizenship: National Passports or Local Ballots? -- tChapter 3. Attrition through Enforcement in the ‘‘Promiseland’’: Overlapping Memberships and the Duties of Governments in Mexican America -- tChapter 4. Multilevel Citizenship in a Federal State: The Case of Noncitizens’ Rights in the United States -- tPART II. Empires and Indigeneity -- tChapter 5. When Did Egyptians Stop Being Ottomans? An Imperial Citizenship Case Study -- tChapter 6. The Su Bao Case and the Layers of Everyday Citizenship in China, 1894–1904 -- tChapter 7. The International Indigenous Rights Discourse and Its Demands for Multilevel Citizenship -- tPART III. Local, Multinational, and Postnational -- tChapter 8. Local Citizenship Politics in Switzerland: Between National Justice and Municipal Particularities -- tChapter 9. Multilevel Citizenship and the Contested Statehood of Bosnia and Herzegovina -- tChapter 10. Citizens of a New Agora: Postnational Citizenship and International Economic Institutions -- tChapter 11. Sites of Citizenship, Politics of Scales -- tContributors -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aCitizenship has come to mean legal and political equality within a sovereign nation-state; in international law, only states may determine who is and who is not a citizen. But such unitary status is the historical exception: before sovereign nation-states became the prevailing form of political organization, citizenship had a range of definitions and applications. Today, nonstate communities and jurisdictions both below and above the state level are once again becoming important sources of rights, allegiance, and status, thereby constituting renewed forms of multilevel citizenship. For example, while the European Union protects the nation-state's right to determine its own members, the project to construct a democratic polity beyond national borders challenges the sovereignty of member governments.Multilevel Citizenship disputes the dominant narrative of citizenship as a homogeneous status that can be bestowed only by nation-states. The contributors examine past and present case studies that complicate the meaning and function of citizenship, including residual allegiance to empires, constitutional rights that are accessible to noncitizens, and the nonstate allegiance of nomadic nations. Their analyses consider the inconsistencies and exceptions of national citizenship as a political concept, such as overlapping jurisdictions and shared governance, as well as the emergent forms of sub- or supranational citizenships. Multilevel Citizenship captures the complexity of citizenship in practice, both at different levels and in different places and times.Contributors: Elizabeth F. Cohen, Elizabeth Dale, Will Hanley, Marc Helbling, Türküler Isiksel, Jenn Kinney, Sheryl Lightfoot, Willem Maas, Catherine Neveu, Luicy Pedroza, Eldar Sarajli&#263;, Rogers M. Smith.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF tit